# Food Truck Activation Kit A: Pitch and Card
## Liana Banyan Corporation, Cooperative-Class Merchant Onboarding
### Status: READY FOR FOUNDER REVIEW / Floor mode available TODAY

---

> **Kit Purpose:** Founder (or any LB cooperative-class member acting as introducer) walks up to a local food truck owner, has a real human conversation, and invites them to join as a business node on the platform. This kit is a repeatable template. Any member can use it. The introducer gets attribution credit in the platform ledger when the merchant joins.

> **One sentence of what LB IS today:** Liana Banyan is a cooperative platform where local businesses take online orders and offer weekly meal-prep subscriptions to members, and where Workers, Builders, and Creators keep 83.3% of every transaction, with a platform margin of Cost+20% and a $5/year structural membership fee. No VC. No ads. No extraction.

---

## §1. The Walk-Up Pitch (2 minutes spoken)

### Opening: 10-Second Permission Ask

You say this BEFORE handing anything. You're asking for a minute, not launching into a pitch.

---

**Variant A , Busy mid-rush** (owner is at the window, working)
*(~15 words spoken; step back after so they can keep working)*

> "Hey, I won't hold you up. Slow moment, I'd love to show you something I built. Card okay?"

*If they nod or say sure: hand the card. Say nothing else until they have a break. Come back.*

---

**Variant B , Slow afternoon** (truck open, owner visible, no line)
*(~25 words spoken)*

> "Got a minute? I built something for local food businesses, and I'd like you to be one of the first ones I test it with. Can I show you?"

---

**Variant C , Post-shift relaxed** (truck closed or closing, owner packing down)
*(~30 words spoken)*

> "I know you're wrapping up. I won't take long. I've been building a platform for local businesses, and I wanted to walk you through it while I had the chance. Sound okay?"

---

### The 60-Second Pitch

*(Read this aloud to practice; aim for conversational, not memorized. Adapt as needed.)*

---

"I built a cooperative platform. It's called Liana Banyan. You're already running your truck. This adds three things: a website for your business, a subscription engine so your customers can pre-commit to a weekly meal-prep order, and a scheduling app called Atlas that lets you plan ingredient buys before the week starts. The platform keeps Cost+20% as a margin. That's it. No VC taking a cut. No ads on your customers. No lock-in.

The membership fee is $5 a year. That's the structural bylaw, not a promotion. Workers, Builders, and Creators keep 83.3% of every transaction on the platform.

You set the menu. You set the price. Your customers pay half a week in advance through subscriptions, so you know what to buy before you buy it. Less waste, more predictable cash flow.

I filed 21 provisional patents at the USPTO covering the technical architecture. The platform isn't backed by outside investors. It's designed to be owned by the people who use it.

That's what it is."

*(~155 words, ~65 seconds at conversational pace)*

---

### The 30-Second Close

*(This is the ask. Say it plainly.)*

---

"Here's what I'm asking. I'd like to put your truck on the platform. You keep running your truck exactly as you always have. This adds online ordering, subscriptions for your customers, and cash-flow planning through Atlas. It takes about 10 minutes to walk through the setup with you.

If you say yes: you get a node on the platform, I get credit for the introduction, and we get to work.

If you say no: we shook hands and I learned something. Either way, we're good."

*(~80 words, ~35 seconds)*

---

### Card Handoff Line

*(Said as you physically hand them the card)*

---

"This card has the link. Scan the QR or type the URL. Takes about five minutes to walk through. Call me if you have questions, my number's on the back."

---

